{
  "updated_summary": "The Nobel Prize ceremony commenced in a grand, ornate concert hall filled with an audience in formal attire, setting a solemn yet celebratory tone. The stage was elaborately decorated with a massive floral wall of red and pink roses, flanked by vertical light fixtures and pink floral spheres, with a bronze bust of Alfred Nobel prominently at the center. An orchestra, identified as The Royal Philharmonic, performed a march by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart under warm, golden lighting, with a large Swedish flag displayed above them. A female conductor in a black embellished dress led the ensemble with expressive gestures, while close-ups showed deeply focused musicians. Dignitaries, including a woman in a shimmering silver gown with a tiara and sash, and a man in a tuxedo with a medal, were seated in ornate blue and gold chairs. The camera panned across attentive guests, including an audience member in white headwear and another in a black turban, before revealing the grand stage with a blue carpet and a large white 'N' emblem. As elegant orchestral music swelled, an announcer introduced the Nobel laureates: Physics Laureates David Thouless, Duncan Haldane, and Michael Kosterlitz; Chemistry Laureates Jean-Pierre Sauvage, Fraser Stoddart, and Ben Feringa; Medicine Laureate Yoshinori Ohsumi; and Economics Laureates Oliver Hart and Bengt Holmström. Professor Carl-Henrik Heldin, Chairman of the Board of the Nobel Foundation, a man with gray hair and glasses in a black tuxedo, white bow tie, blue sash, and gold medal, delivered a formal speech from a marble podium, emphasizing the Nobel Prize's role as a source of inspiration and Alfred Nobel's legacy. He welcomed the King of Sweden and Queen of Sweden, along with other dignitaries including the Prince of Sweden and Princess of Sweden, seated in ornate blue and gold chairs. Heldin referenced President Juan Manuel Santos receiving the Nobel Peace Prize in Oslo and highlighted Nobel's cosmopolitan nature and influence by the Enlightenment. He discussed historical economic expansion and the impact of nationalism, contrasting it with globalization and international trade, noting that many of Alfred Nobel's contemporary concerns still resonate today. Heldin stressed the importance of believing in science, facts, and knowledge, especially in times of growing fear, populism, and questioning of science. He articulated Alfred Nobel's vision to reward those who have "conferred the greatest benefit to mankind," emphasizing the "power of example" and the desire for the prize to "contribute to a better world." He also spoke about the Nobel organization's public engagement, future initiatives, and the new Nobel Center in Stockholm. The ceremony included a musical interlude, a Quadrille from The Wedding of the Eiffel Tower by Jean Taillefer, performed by the orchestra, featuring a harp and various instruments, all under warm, formal lighting, with '#NobelPrize' and 'Nobelprize.org' visible on-screen throughout."
}
